Appendix 1

The first fix that needed to be made to the data was getting rid of the repeat values.

Fix1 <- CroqPain %>% 
  arrange(STOR) %>% 
  unique()

We then examined the distributions of each individual variable to see the shape of their distributions. 

hist.data.frame(CroqPain)

ggplot(stack(Fix1), aes(x=ind, y = values))+
  geom_boxplot()


We noticed the very high outlier in EARN and decided to investigate further.

ggplot(Fix1, aes(x = EARN)) + 
  geom_boxplot()


This outlier was off by a factor of 1000 from the rest of the data. We realized that this earning variable is in $1000s so this data point may have not been scaled. This is consistent with the data table in the case, so we divided this point by 1000.

Fix2 <- Fix1 %>% 
  mutate(EARN = ifelse(STOR == 1, EARN/1000, EARN))


Looking at the distribution now, it is more normally distributed

ggplot(Fix2, aes(x = EARN)) + 
  geom_boxplot()


We examined all other variables that contained outliers. None of the outliers seemed unreasonable to include in the data so no other changes were made.
We did notice that looking at the sum of all the age breakdowns for population did not sum to the total population provided. This seemed logical since children under 15 were not accounted for in the groupings. However, we noticed that for Store 57 there was 40 people that were not accounted for in the total. We are assuming this small difference is due to a rounding error and will not be making any changes to the data regarding this discrepency.

Fix2 %>% 
  mutate(total2 = P15 + P25 + P35 + P45 + P55) %>% 
  mutate(dif = total - total2) %>% 
  select(total, total2, dif, P15, P25, P35, P45, P55) %>% 
  tail(10)

Looking at this correlation matrix, we see that certain variables are highly correlated.

Appendix 2-1, B.1

The total population and the different populations for age are highly correlated.

result <- correlation(
  CroqPainFix, 
  vars = c(
    "total", "P15", "P25", "P35", "P45", "P55")
  )
plot(result, nrobs = 1000)


Because of the high correlation, we know that all of these variables cannot be in the model together because it will have high multicollinearity.

Appendix 2-1, B.2

Additionally, we looked at the capital investment, price, and size variable that had strong correlations.

result <- correlation(
  CroqPainFix, 
  vars = c(
    "SIZE", "PRICE", "K")
  )
plot(result, nrobs = 1000)


These three variables will not be able to be in the model together because of high multicollinearity.

Appendix 2-1, C.1

We adjusted the data to account for the per capita proportions of several variables.

CroqPainFix <- CroqPainFix %>% 
  mutate(EARNpc = EARN/total,
         P15pc = P15/total,
         P25pc = P25/total,
         P35pc = P35/total,
         P45pc = P45/total,
         P55pc = P55/total,
         COMPpc = COMP/total,
         NCOMPpc = NCOMP/total,
         NRESTpc = NREST/total) %>% 
  select(-total, -P15, -P25, -P35, -P45, -P55, -COMP, -NCOMP, -NREST)

Appendix 2-1, D

CroqPainFix <- CroqPainFix %>%

Whis look approximately normal so we will proceed with this variable.

Appendix 2-2

We took a top down approach to building the regression

Appendix 2-2, A

We first ran the model with all of the variables

result <- regress(
  CroqPainFix, 
  rvar = "EARNpc", 
  evar = c(
    "K", "SIZE", "EMPL", "INC", "PRICE", "CLI", "P15pc", "P25pc", 
    "P35pc", "P45pc", "P55pc", "COMPpc", "NCOMPpc", "NRESTpc"
  )
)

result <- regress(
  CroqPainFix, 
  rvar = "EARNpc", 
  evar = c(
    "K", "SIZE", "EMPL", "PRICE", "CLI", "P15pc", "P25pc",
